think first write attempt to ~/treasure-chest/sandbox-test.txt inside Cursor's own default per-tool sandbox failed with sandbox-exec: sandbox_apply: Operation not permitted -- a nested-Seatbelt error, not a plain permission denial, which itself hints an outer Seatbelt profile (ai-jail) is already applied and will not let Cursor's own wrapper stack a second one on top.
think re-ran with required_permissions all to bypass Cursor's own sandbox wrapper specifically, to isolate whether the block was Cursor's ordinary workspace-only sandbox (which every session has, jailed or not) versus a true outer OS-level fence.
think with Cursor's own sandbox layer bypassed, mkdir -p ~/treasure-chest still failed with a clean Operation not permitted (no nested-sandbox noise this time) -- this is the decisive signal, since Cursor's own sandbox was out of the picture and something at the OS process level still refused to create a directory directly under $HOME.
think checked whoami, hostname, ls ~, and mount to confirm this is the real host filesystem and real $HOME (not a private jailed copy) -- .antigravity, .aws, .cargo, and other real dotfiles are all visible, and the named_gaps field in the prior session log already says the GUI launcher has no private-$HOME step yet, so seeing the real home tree is expected and not itself a leak.
think confirmed via find / -maxdepth 4 -iname "*treasure*" that no treasure-chest directory exists anywhere visible on this filesystem, which matches "the jail is working" rather than "the folder never got made" -- Keaton's real Terminal.app session (outside the jail) can see and made the folder; this jailed session, sharing the same real $HOME path, is blocked at the Seatbelt write-fence boundary from ever creating it.
obs the write fence documented in the prior session's SBPL profile (repo + /tmp + /private/tmp + /private/var/folders allowed, deny default) is exactly what this live test exercised and confirmed -- a plain mkdir at $HOME level, once Cursor's own separate sandbox wrapper was taken out of the loop, still hit the outer jail's deny-default rule.
obs this is a genuinely useful second, independent witness of the same launcher tools/cursor_jail_macos.rish already tests programmatically -- this one ran from inside a live Cursor agent window rather than from the witness script, closing the gap between "the launcher's own --print-profile output looks right" and "an agent actually running inside it cannot escape."
